Admission Criteria    | Postbaccalaureate Prehealth Studies | New York University                                       NEW YORK UNIVERSITY     ARTS AND SCIENCE     COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE     GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE           NYU College of Arts & Science     Postbaccalaureate Prehealth Studies Program                         Home       Program       Admission to our Program       Current Students       Applying to Health Professional Schools              Admission Criteria            Application Process              Letters of Recommendation              Linkage Programs              Glide Year         Linkage Programs       FAQs       Contact Us               Home > Applying to Health Professional Schools > Admission Criteria     Admission Criteria   Schools of the health professions are looking for mature, well-rounded people who are interested in the health arts and in their patients as people. They want diverse classes representing a variety of socioeconomic and ethnic groups. Applicants should be well-read, intellectually curious and have some sense of “life” in the larger meaning of the word. Thus, the fact that you may be a bit (or a lot) older than most applicants will NOT be held against you. In fact, professional school admissions officers frequently tell us that they like seeing applications from people who have done other things in life besides completing their college degrees.      Decisions to admit candidates are based upon multiple factors that are to a degree unique for each school. In general, however, all schools are looking for (1) evidence of an ability to accomplish the academic work necessary to progress through the school’s curriculum as demonstrated on the candidate’s college records and on the MCAT (or DAT or other admissions test) scores and (2) evidence of personal qualities and attributes needed in health care as demonstrated in the applicant’s personal statement, recommendations, extracurricular and community involvement, and health-related volunteer work. Medical schools also require personal interviews of selected candidates as part of their admissions criteria.     More information about readiness and preparation can be found on the main NYU Prehealth website .                     Grades            Grades       One of the most important criteria considered by professional schools is an applicant’s grades. This does not mean, however, that you should develop an antagonistically competitive attitude vis-a-vis your classmates and your instructors. Professional schools set no limit on the number of NYU students they accept. Helping another student will never hurt your grades, and it may very well help to clarify your own understanding of the subject. At NYU, as everywhere, a certain amount of self-created anxiety exists among the undergraduate prehealth students about their grades. We want to diminish this, and we believe our postbaccalaureate students, who have a little more perspective, can help. All students can only try their best; cooperation, understanding, sympathy, and help can make a great difference. Indeed, our very best and most successful students exhibit precisely these qualities. Incidentally, such qualities will not be looked down upon by medical schools in considering who they want as future physicians.       Most NYU postbaccalaureate students have earned admirable records as undergraduates. For those who do not have very good undergraduate records, there are usually two scenarios:          You completed your undergraduate education several years ago and you have either matured greatly in the meantime or have resolved the issues that previously prevented you from doing well. Provided you earn excellent grades in your prehealth courses, your undergraduate record will be of lesser importance than for new graduates. Although your overall average will be low, professional schools will be able to see the vast difference between your two records. In addition, explanations can be made in both your letter of recommendation from us and in your personal essay as to why your older undergraduate record is less than perfect.      You are a very recent graduate (three years ago or less). Schools will be particularly concerned about whether your personal situation has changed sufficiently in a relatively short amount of time so that you can be a successful medical student. If you fall into this category, speak to an advisor about your particular case. In general, the undergraduate record carries less weight the older it becomes.           BCPM (Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Math) GPA Calculator                           Tests            Admission Tests       Some schools of the health professions require specific admissions tests, like the MCAT for medical schools and the DAT for dental schools. Both the MCAT and DAT are designed to assess mastery of the basic skills and concepts that are requisite for the successful completion of medical or dental school. The MCAT Verbal Reasoning, Physical Sciences, and Biological Sciences sections consist of multiple choice questions, and the Writing Sample requires two essays. The DAT covers the Natural Sciences (biology, general chemistry and organic chemistry), Perceptual Ability (two- and three-dimensional problem-solving), Reading Comprehension (dental and basic sciences), and Quantitative Reasoning.         Reading and Problem-Solving Skills    Reading and problem-solving skills on these tests are very important. On the MCAT, the question format for the two science sections (Biological Sciences and Physical Sciences) includes written descriptions of phenomena followed by a series of questions all relating back to the written passage. Additional questions are independent of any passage and each other. These sections thereby test your skills in the areas of information recall, reading comprehension, interpretation of data, application of concepts and evaluation.       The Verbal Reasoning section consists of several passages, each 500 to 600 words long, taken from humanities, social sciences, and some areas in natural sciences, accompanied by 5 to 10 questions. Most students report that the examination does not test what you have learned so much as it tests how well you can analyze data and information. Your capability to read and solve problems is very important. You have a direct interest, therefore, in developing your critical thinking skills to their utmost.       Many medical schools now emphasize how students learn and solve problems rather than how much they know. With the explosion of scientific information in this century, educators realize that it is impossible to memorize all the facts that are important, and which are ever-changing. Instead, they emphasize the need to approach illness differently and the necessity for health professionals to be active in continuing education throughout their lives. Several medical schools have thus instituted fundamental curricular changes in how students are taught. You would thus be well served by learning how to approach and solve problems and how to get information.         Writing Skills     The Writing Sample asks students to write two 30-minute essays, generally commenting on statements made by famous persons. You will comment neither on anything related to the health professions nor on controversial topics where your opinions might cause an admissions committee to take a biased opinion against your application. If your writing skills are poor because your first language is not English, because you simply are not a “good” writer, or because your undergraduate writing preparation was inadequate, rise to this challenge and meet it. Ask an advisor for help in course selection.                             Experience            Healthcare Experience       Long-term experience in the health-care field is essential before and while you are taking the required science courses. Although healthcare experience is important for all applicants, it is particularly so for postbaccalaureate students because professional schools will be concerned about your recent change of career and life plans.       You should become well-informed about the career decision you are making. Your commitment to a career in the health professions should be supplemented with direct experience in a health-care setting. There are countless ways in which you can acquire experience. The easiest way is through volunteer work in a hospital, hospice, clinic, ambulance corps or special facility (such as a nursing home, home for the severely disabled, etc.). It does not matter where you choose to work. Most students choose an establishment close to either home or school.       Paid positions are equally valuable, and if you are working in a health care setting you should continue to do so while taking classes.       Please visit the Preprofessional Advising Center or the Prehealth website under “Prehealth Forms” for a complete list of nearby hospital volunteer contacts.       Pre-vet students should keep in mind that they need even more extensive experience, particularly with large animals.                             Individual Letters            Individual Letters of Recommendation       Letters of recommendation are an important part of your application to schools of the health professions, both from faculty and, in some cases, practitioners. The science courses at NYU are large, but we urge you to make contact with your professors (not just your lab TAs or recitation instructors) early and seek depth and clarification in your studies. You might even pursue scientific research. This will not only help you academically, but can help you form an important relationship with a professor who can write to schools on your behalf.       If you have attended graduate school, or are a recent graduate from college, you should also be able to include a letter of recommendation by a former professor from those programs. Some health professional schools might even require it.       Some health professional schools require letters from practitioners who can write on your behalf. For example, if you are applying to dental schools or osteopathic schools, you will be generally expected to have the support of a dentist or osteopathic physician (respectively) to recommend you to the profession. As noted above, you are also expected to gain experience and familiarity with the profession to which you are committing yourself, so you should spend some time with a dentist, osteopath, physical therapist, etc. to help you become more informed about the field.       These “outside” letters of recommendation will be appended to our Committee letter submitted in support of your application.      More Important Details on Letters of Recommendation                             Committee Letter            Committee Letter of Evaluation to Schools of the Health Professions       NYU writes a comprehensive letter of evaluation for every student in our postbaccalaureate prehealth program who is applying to schools in the health professions and who has complied with our policies and standards. The Prehealth Committee has an extensive evaluation process for our prehealth students, enabling the Committee to write a thorough letter. We gather information about you from different sources while you are taking classes here and use that information when writing your composite letter of evaluation. These letters are very personal and confidential in nature: They are never form letters in any sense.        Committee Interviews     During the spring semester of the year in which you will send your applications to professional schools (which is actually one calendar year before you intend to enter professional school), you will participate in prehealth interviews coordinated by the Preprofessional Advising Center. Prior to this, at the end of the fall semester, you will have obtained a set of autobiographical forms from the office and returned them along with personal statements as indicated in the accompanying instructions. Each student will be assigned an interview with a faculty member or administrator. Consider the interview to be somewhat like a professional school interview. We want to learn more about you.       Information from the interviews and your essays is used to compile a committee letter of evaluation. All outside recommendations sent to our office within the specified time period are attached to the committee letter which we will send to health professional schools only. Information in your file (evaluation sheets, outside letters of recommendation, your essays) cannot be forwarded to other graduate programs or to other postbaccalaureate programs should you decide to switch schools. Admission Criteria    | Postbaccalaureate Prehealth Studies | New York University                                       NEW YORK UNIVERSITY     ARTS AND SCIENCE     COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE     GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE           NYU College of Arts & Science     Postbaccalaureate Prehealth Studies Program                         Home       Program       Admission to our Program       Current Students       Applying to Health Professional Schools              Admission Criteria            Application Process              Letters of Recommendation              Linkage Programs              Glide Year         Linkage Programs       FAQs       Contact Us               Home > Applying to Health Professional Schools > Admission Criteria     Admission Criteria   Schools of the health professions are looking for mature, well-rounded people who are interested in the health arts and in their patients as people. They want diverse classes representing a variety of socioeconomic and ethnic groups. Applicants should be well-read, intellectually curious and have some sense of “life” in the larger meaning of the word. Thus, the fact that you may be a bit (or a lot) older than most applicants will NOT be held against you. In fact, professional school admissions officers frequently tell us that they like seeing applications from people who have done other things in life besides completing their college degrees.      Decisions to admit candidates are based upon multiple factors that are to a degree unique for each school. In general, however, all schools are looking for (1) evidence of an ability to accomplish the academic work necessary to progress through the school’s curriculum as demonstrated on the candidate’s college records and on the MCAT (or DAT or other admissions test) scores and (2) evidence of personal qualities and attributes needed in health care as demonstrated in the applicant’s personal statement, recommendations, extracurricular and community involvement, and health-related volunteer work. Medical schools also require personal interviews of selected candidates as part of their admissions criteria.     More information about readiness and preparation can be found on the main NYU Prehealth website .                     Grades            Grades       One of the most important criteria considered by professional schools is an applicant’s grades. This does not mean, however, that you should develop an antagonistically competitive attitude vis-a-vis your classmates and your instructors. Professional schools set no limit on the number of NYU students they accept. Helping another student will never hurt your grades, and it may very well help to clarify your own understanding of the subject. At NYU, as everywhere, a certain amount of self-created anxiety exists among the undergraduate prehealth students about their grades. We want to diminish this, and we believe our postbaccalaureate students, who have a little more perspective, can help. All students can only try their best; cooperation, understanding, sympathy, and help can make a great difference. Indeed, our very best and most successful students exhibit precisely these qualities. Incidentally, such qualities will not be looked down upon by medical schools in considering who they want as future physicians.       Most NYU postbaccalaureate students have earned admirable records as undergraduates. For those who do not have very good undergraduate records, there are usually two scenarios:          You completed your undergraduate education several years ago and you have either matured greatly in the meantime or have resolved the issues that previously prevented you from doing well. Provided you earn excellent grades in your prehealth courses, your undergraduate record will be of lesser importance than for new graduates. Although your overall average will be low, professional schools will be able to see the vast difference between your two records. In addition, explanations can be made in both your letter of recommendation from us and in your personal essay as to why your older undergraduate record is less than perfect.      You are a very recent graduate (three years ago or less). Schools will be particularly concerned about whether your personal situation has changed sufficiently in a relatively short amount of time so that you can be a successful medical student. If you fall into this category, speak to an advisor about your particular case. In general, the undergraduate record carries less weight the older it becomes.           BCPM (Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Math) GPA Calculator                           Tests            Admission Tests       Some schools of the health professions require specific admissions tests, like the MCAT for medical schools and the DAT for dental schools. Both the MCAT and DAT are designed to assess mastery of the basic skills and concepts that are requisite for the successful completion of medical or dental school. The MCAT Verbal Reasoning, Physical Sciences, and Biological Sciences sections consist of multiple choice questions, and the Writing Sample requires two essays. The DAT covers the Natural Sciences (biology, general chemistry and organic chemistry), Perceptual Ability (two- and three-dimensional problem-solving), Reading Comprehension (dental and basic sciences), and Quantitative Reasoning.         Reading and Problem-Solving Skills    Reading and problem-solving skills on these tests are very important. On the MCAT, the question format for the two science sections (Biological Sciences and Physical Sciences) includes written descriptions of phenomena followed by a series of questions all relating back to the written passage. Additional questions are independent of any passage and each other. These sections thereby test your skills in the areas of information recall, reading comprehension, interpretation of data, application of concepts and evaluation.       The Verbal Reasoning section consists of several passages, each 500 to 600 words long, taken from humanities, social sciences, and some areas in natural sciences, accompanied by 5 to 10 questions. Most students report that the examination does not test what you have learned so much as it tests how well you can analyze data and information. Your capability to read and solve problems is very important. You have a direct interest, therefore, in developing your critical thinking skills to their utmost.       Many medical schools now emphasize how students learn and solve problems rather than how much they know. With the explosion of scientific information in this century, educators realize that it is impossible to memorize all the facts that are important, and which are ever-changing. Instead, they emphasize the need to approach illness differently and the necessity for health professionals to be active in continuing education throughout their lives. Several medical schools have thus instituted fundamental curricular changes in how students are taught. You would thus be well served by learning how to approach and solve problems and how to get information.         Writing Skills     The Writing Sample asks students to write two 30-minute essays, generally commenting on statements made by famous persons. You will comment neither on anything related to the health professions nor on controversial topics where your opinions might cause an admissions committee to take a biased opinion against your application. If your writing skills are poor because your first language is not English, because you simply are not a “good” writer, or because your undergraduate writing preparation was inadequate, rise to this challenge and meet it. Ask an advisor for help in course selection.                             Experience            Healthcare Experience       Long-term experience in the health-care field is essential before and while you are taking the required science courses. Although healthcare experience is important for all applicants, it is particularly so for postbaccalaureate students because professional schools will be concerned about your recent change of career and life plans.       You should become well-informed about the career decision you are making. Your commitment to a career in the health professions should be supplemented with direct experience in a health-care setting. There are countless ways in which you can acquire experience. The easiest way is through volunteer work in a hospital, hospice, clinic, ambulance corps or special facility (such as a nursing home, home for the severely disabled, etc.). It does not matter where you choose to work. Most students choose an establishment close to either home or school.       Paid positions are equally valuable, and if you are working in a health care setting you should continue to do so while taking classes.       Please visit the Preprofessional Advising Center or the Prehealth website under “Prehealth Forms” for a complete list of nearby hospital volunteer contacts.       Pre-vet students should keep in mind that they need even more extensive experience, particularly with large animals.                             Individual Letters            Individual Letters of Recommendation       Letters of recommendation are an important part of your application to schools of the health professions, both from faculty and, in some cases, practitioners. The science courses at NYU are large, but we urge you to make contact with your professors (not just your lab TAs or recitation instructors) early and seek depth and clarification in your studies. You might even pursue scientific research. This will not only help you academically, but can help you form an important relationship with a professor who can write to schools on your behalf.       If you have attended graduate school, or are a recent graduate from college, you should also be able to include a letter of recommendation by a former professor from those programs. Some health professional schools might even require it.       Some health professional schools require letters from practitioners who can write on your behalf. For example, if you are applying to dental schools or osteopathic schools, you will be generally expected to have the support of a dentist or osteopathic physician (respectively) to recommend you to the profession. As noted above, you are also expected to gain experience and familiarity with the profession to which you are committing yourself, so you should spend some time with a dentist, osteopath, physical therapist, etc. to help you become more informed about the field.       These “outside” letters of recommendation will be appended to our Committee letter submitted in support of your application.      More Important Details on Letters of Recommendation                             Committee Letter            Committee Letter of Evaluation to Schools of the Health Professions       NYU writes a comprehensive letter of evaluation for every student in our postbaccalaureate prehealth program who is applying to schools in the health professions and who has complied with our policies and standards. The Prehealth Committee has an extensive evaluation process for our prehealth students, enabling the Committee to write a thorough letter. We gather information about you from different sources while you are taking classes here and use that information when writing your composite letter of evaluation. These letters are very personal and confidential in nature: They are never form letters in any sense.        Committee Interviews     During the spring semester of the year in which you will send your applications to professional schools (which is actually one calendar year before you intend to enter professional school), you will participate in prehealth interviews coordinated by the Preprofessional Advising Center. Prior to this, at the end of the fall semester, you will have obtained a set of autobiographical forms from the office and returned them along with personal statements as indicated in the accompanying instructions. Each student will be assigned an interview with a faculty member or administrator. Consider the interview to be somewhat like a professional school interview. We want to learn more about you.       Information from the interviews and your essays is used to compile a committee letter of evaluation. All outside recommendations sent to our office within the specified time period are attached to the committee letter which we will send to health professional schools only. Information in your file (evaluation sheets, outside letters of recommendation, your essays) cannot be forwarded to other graduate programs or to other postbaccalaureate programs should you decide to switch schools.
